Understanding information diffusion in microblogging platforms is critical for analyzing civic discourse, yet traditional Agent-Based Modeling faces severe computational bottlenecks at scale. This thesis introduces a high-performance Discrete-Event Simulation (DES) engine, implemented in Zig, to model continuous-time information cascades on the decentralized Bluesky network. By formalizing the platform as a Time-Varying Heterogeneous Graph, the study integrates the Continuous-Time Independent Cascade (CTIC) model with Activity-Driven user session dynamics. The simulation is empirically calibrated using real-world telemetry extracted from the Bluesky Firehose dataset, defining precise distributions for user session lengths, interaction rates, and post-creation intervals. Executed across sampled topologies of up to one million users, the DES approach achieves linear scalability and stable steady-state behavior. Results indicate that structural virality and cascade depth scale sub-linearly with cascade size, and that timeline starvation is heavily influenced by session timing rather than a user's network degree. Furthermore, under a uniform, content-agnostic behavioral policy, the model demonstrates that topological position alone does not dictate cascade size, establishing a structural baseline that highlights the necessity of content-aware mechanics to accurately replicate real-world influencer dynamics.

*Keywords*: Information Diffusion, Discrete-Event Simulation (DES), Continuous-Time Independent Cascade (CTIC), Bluesky/AT Protocol, Activity-Driven Networks, Structural Virality
